{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568171"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:10:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:10:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19523"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19523"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.78,0.04,0.1,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12293"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86020"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12293"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70281"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2409"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29430"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29513"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86020"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 51-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her fingernails show thinning with loss of normal convexity, and the nail plates appear concave (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is associated with this finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Infective endocarditis","Iron deficiency anaemia","Hyperthyroidism","Psoriatic arthritis","Chronic liver disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows spoon-shaped nails (koilonychia), where the normally convex nail plate becomes thin and concave. \u003Cstrong\u003EIron deficiency anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is the condition most commonly associated with koilonychia, though it can occasionally be seen in other conditions or due to occupational trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfective endocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause nail changes including splinter haemorrhages and Janeway lesions, but koilonychia is not typically associated with endocarditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperthyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E can cause nail changes including separation of the nail from the nail bed but does not typically cause koilonychia. Other thyroid-associated nail changes include brittleness and rapid growth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriatic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes pitting, separation of the nail from the nail bed, and oil-drop discolouration of nails. Spoon-shaped nails are not a feature of psoriatic nail disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic liver disease\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with nail changes including clubbing, but not typically with koilonychia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen koilonychia is identified, further investigation for iron deficiency anaemia is warranted, including a full blood count, and iron studies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Koilonychia (spoon-shaped nails) is characterised by concave nail plates and is commonly associated with iron deficiency anaemia.","Nail changes can be important physical signs of underlying systemic disease and should be carefully examined.","Iron studies and full blood count are required to investigate for associated iron deficiency anaemia when koilonychia is identified."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Walker J, Baran R, V\u00e9lez N, Jellinek N. Koilonychia: an update on pathophysiology, differential diagnosis and clinical relevance. J Eur Acad Dermatol Venereol. 2016;30(11):1985-1991. doi:10.1111/jdv.13610"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70281"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19523"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21604"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21604"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/wre7p3qgwP4ooA0qHsLk7Eeu6oEbJh.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/wre7p3qgwP4ooA0qHsLk7Eeu6oEbJh.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":321}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70281"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-18T21:30:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-18T21:31:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12293"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86020"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"Ge